articles.title: Observations
articles.summary: The article outlines a busy November for SJAA members, including a general meeting featuring Martin Haske discussing the Space Telescope, which serves as a prelude to a December tour of the Lockheed mock-up. It also references October's grating occultation reports, encourages participation in a "November expedition," and announces a Fremont Peak star party scheduled near the end of the month.

articles.title: SJAA Officer Changes
articles.summary: Kevin Medlock has resigned from his positions as president and board member of the SJAA. The board appointed Jack Zeiders to fill a board vacancy after a close vote, and "Yours Truly" was appointed as the new president. The author congratulates Jack Zeiders on his new board position.

articles.title: Back-Up For Refreshments Duty Needed
articles.summary: Rita Miram, who has long provided refreshments for general meetings, is seeking a back-up for her duties. She plans to continue until at least the new year but needs someone to cover for the few times she might miss. Responsibilities are light, involving preparing coffee and bringing snacks, with all expenses reimbursed by the SJAA.

articles.title: Club Telescopes Up For Loan
articles.summary: The SJAA is making its 6-inch and 12.5-inch telescopes available for a two-month loan period; members interested in borrowing can contact George Delwart or Wolf Hanisch. Additionally, Ron Probst is volunteering to repair the club's 14.5-inch telescope, with hopes of it being ready for star parties next summer.

articles.title: Astronomy Magazine
articles.summary: Shea Pratt is reminding members to renew or subscribe to Astronomy Magazine through SJAA at a discounted rate of $12 per year. Subscriptions must be submitted to her by November 15th at the latest to qualify for the special pricing.

articles.title: Membership Renewals
articles.summary: This article serves as an announcement listing individuals who failed to renew their SJAA membership or bulletin subscription in June, stating that the November bulletin will be their last if they do not renew. It outlines the annual membership fees: $18 for regular SJAA membership (including Sky & Telescope), $12 for junior membership, and $7 for a non-member bulletin subscription, along with payment instructions.

articles.title: Sanborn Canyon S.P.
articles.summary: Jay Freeman reported on the Sanborn Canyon star party held on Oct. 24, attended by several members and guests. The event was cut short due to unfavorable weather conditions, specifically high cirrus clouds and fog, leading attendees to leave by 8 PM for a different gathering in Los Gatos. Organizers plan to reschedule another star party later in the winter.

articles.title: SAO & Revised NGC Charts
articles.summary: The article contains two main announcements: Steve Greenberg is making Smithsonian Astronomical Observatory (SAO) charts available to interested members, with a possibility for Revised NGC (RNGC) Charts if there is enough interest. Additionally, the outgoing editor of the SJAA Ephemeris bulletin, Denni, bids farewell, thanks contributors, and introduces Steve Greenberg and Patty Minter as the new editors.

articles.title: GRAZE INFORMATION
articles.summary: This document provides comprehensive logistical and astronomical information for an upcoming lunar graze event involving the star 36 Geminorum. Scheduled for the late evening of November 14-15, 1981, northwest of Greenfield in California's Salinas Valley, it details observing circumstances, precise timing, location, communication protocols, and extensive celestial coordinates for participants. Observers are instructed on preparation, recording times, and how to obtain weather updates via phone or CB radio.

articles.title: GRAZE REPORT -- Los Banos, Oct. 18
articles.summary: A lunar graze expedition to Los Banos on October 18/19 was deemed a "big success," with multiple events observed across nine stations by a dedicated group of astronomers. Despite challenges like traffic, cows, and flies, observers enjoyed an excellent, dark sky and successfully gathered data to help confirm or reject a probable northward shift indicated by Dr. Dunham. The report also thanks participants and announces a future graze event.

articles.title: JUST TOUCHED
articles.summary: Janice Smith recounts her personal and often humorous experience on an October 19th lunar graze expedition, an amateur astronomy event. Despite numerous technical difficulties, including equipment issues and losing her recorded data, she found the visual phenomenon of the star disappearing behind the moon deeply moving and plans to participate in future observations. The article highlights the unique challenges and profound rewards of amateur astronomy.

articles.title: ASTEROID OCCULTATION 20 Sep 81
articles.summary: This article is a first-person account of an amateur astronomer's challenging attempt to observe an asteroid occultation on September 20, 1981, from Loma Prietta. Despite extensive preparation and the presence of fellow observers, the night was fraught with difficulties, including trouble locating the target star, a critical telescope mirror malfunction requiring a hurried repair in the dark, and ultimately, the failure to observe the occultation itself. The observer reflects on the experience as a bust but acknowledges it as a learning opportunity with hope for future attempts.

articles.title: THE CELESTIAL TOURIST SPEAKS
articles.summary: The article reports on two amateur astronomy star parties held in September 1981 at Mount Umunhum and Fremont Peak, detailing the various telescopes used and the celestial objects observed, such as double stars and nebulae. It highlights specific observations, telescope performance comparisons, and includes an anecdote about a rattlesnake at one event. The author also provides upcoming observing tips for galaxy clusters and notes on specific NGC objects.

articles.title: NASA Schedules Shuttle Launch for Nov. 4
articles.summary: NASA has rescheduled the second flight of the Space Shuttle Columbia for November 4th, following repairs necessitated by a nitrogen tetroxide spill. The incident required rebonding thermal tiles and replacing insulation blankets, caused by an iron nitrate build-up in a ground pumping unit. The five-day mission is set to land at Edwards AFB, California, with White Sands, New Mexico, as an alternate landing site due to potential rain.

articles.title: Air Force General Named To Head Shuttle Development
articles.summary: Maj. General James A. Abrahamson has been appointed as the associate administrator for Space Transportation Systems at NASA-Headquarters, taking over leadership of Shuttle development and production. He succeeds John F. Yardley, who headed Shuttle development for seven years before moving to McDonnell Douglas Astronautics. Dr. Stanley I. Weiss will continue to direct Shuttle operations.

articles.title: Solar Mesosphere Explorer Successfully Orbited
articles.summary: NASA successfully launched its Solar Mesosphere Explorer (SME) spacecraft into a 336-mile polar orbit on October 6th. The SME's mission is to study the reactions between sunlight, ozone, and other atmospheric constituents, and how ozone is transported in the region from 19 to 55 miles altitude. A secondary payload, the Uosat amateur radio satellite, was also launched to investigate the ionosphere.

articles.title: SBS-2 Successfully Launched
articles.summary: Satellite Business Systems' second domestic communications satellite, SBS-2, was successfully launched by NASA aboard a Delta vehicle on September 24 from Cape Canaveral. The satellite is now in its intended orbit at 134 degrees east longitude and is reported to be functioning nominally.

articles.title: French-Soviet Oreol 3 Launched
articles.summary: The French-Soviet Oreol 3 satellite was launched by the Soviet Union on September 21st to investigate physical processes within Earth's magnetosphere and ionosphere, as well as the nature of the Northern Lights. The satellite achieved an orbit of 380/1920 kilometers, with an inclination of 82.6 degrees and a period of 108.2 minutes.

articles.title: Final Ariane Test Launch Reset for Dec. 14
articles.summary: The European Space Agency's fourth and final Ariane test launch has been rescheduled for December 14. Taking place at Kourou, French Guiana, this launch will carry the Marecs-A (Maritime European Communications Satellite-A) payload.

articles.title: NASA Selects Experiments For First Spacelab Life Science Mission
articles.summary: NASA has chosen twenty-five experiments for the inaugural dedicated Spacelab Life Science Mission (Spacelab 4), set to launch aboard the Space Shuttle in October 1985. These experiments will utilize a specialized spaceborne biological laboratory within a Spacelab double habital module, focusing on areas like cardiovascular, vestibular, renal, hematology, immunology, muscle, bone, and general biological studies.

articles.title: NASA Assigns Official to White House Space Policy Review
articles.summary: NASA has assigned Issac I. Gillam IV, director of the Dryden Flight Research Center, as a special assistant to the NASA Administrator, detailing him to the White House Office of Science and Technology. He will participate in an ongoing space policy review led by presidential science adviser Jay Keworth. This review aims to define U.S. space activities for future years and is expected to conclude by the end of the year.

articles.title: NASA Submits Additional Budget Cut Proposals to OMB
articles.summary: NASA submitted recommendations to the Office of Management and Budget on October 5, detailing how to implement an additional $357 million in budget cuts for Fiscal Year 1982, as proposed by the Reagan Administration. These cuts, which further reduce NASA's budget from an initial $6.7 billion to $5.755 billion, are likely to impact programs such as the Galileo Jupiter mission and the Centaur Dpper Stage, potentially leading to their cancellation or delay.

articles.title: India Developing Two New Launch Vehicles
articles.summary: India is actively developing two new launch vehicles: one designed for placing 600 kg satellites into polar orbit, and an augmented version of the SLV-3 (ASLV) capable of launching 150 kg satellites into orbit. These projects are spearheaded by the Indian Space Research Organization (ISRO) and are anticipated to be completed within five to six years.

articles.title: Brazil Plans to Launch 4 Satellites
articles.summary: Brazil plans to launch its first four domestically manufactured satellites—two meteorological and two remote sensing—between 1985 and 1993. The entire space program, including satellites, launch vehicles, and ground systems, is intended to be built and operated within Brazil.

articles.title: And now: Presenting the SJAA FORUM, this month featuring view and counter-view of last month's article, "I Bought a C-14 Because It Was Cheaper Than A Dobson," by Jay Freeman.
articles.summary: The San Jose Astronomical Association (SJAA) is presenting its monthly FORUM, which this month focuses on a discussion and debate. The main topic is last month's article by Jay Freeman, titled "I Bought a C-14 Because It Was Cheaper Than A Dobson," featuring both 'view' and 'counter-view' perspectives.

articles.title: YES, BUT.....
articles.summary: George H. Scotten directly challenges "Jay's" financial justification for purchasing a C-14 telescope, arguing that Jay's cost analysis is flawed due to incorrect compound interest calculations. Scotten suggests more economical and innovative alternatives, such as investing money, building a custom trailer for a large Dobson, or constructing a high-quality 12.5" Newtonian, which he claims can outperform commercial C-14s. He advocates for superior aperture and custom optics, maintaining that while transporting large telescopes presents challenges, it doesn't necessitate a $7000 expenditure.

articles.title: Dear George,
articles.summary: Jay Freeman responds to a letter from George, clarifying financial calculations related to telescope purchases and transportation costs. He explains his practical and economic considerations for choosing a C-14 telescope with a trailer for urban deep-sky observing over building a large custom scope or buying a different vehicle. The document also includes a list of new members for the SJAA.
